english:
  title: Miscellaneous Verses on North Mountain
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To test the heart of a mountain hermit,
    I entered the gate and pretended to be drunk—
    No trace of joy or anger showed,
    Then I knew him truly a man of noble spirit.

    Why do I not dare climb the highest peak?
    Not from fear of the arduous ascent,
    But lest my eyes, grown accustomed to the mountain,
    Should glimpse again the world of men.

    Mountain flowers bloom in hidden valleys,
    Wishing to announce the spring within these heights,
    Yet who truly governs their blooming and falling?
    Most who dwell here are those deep in meditation.

    The mountain hermit ventures forth but rarely—
    The ancient path is buried beneath verdant moss.
    He rightly fears the dusty world of men
    Might profane the moonlight on his green vines.
  footnotes:
    - '녹라월 (green vine moonlight): A poetic image representing the purity and seclusion of mountain life, where the hermit witnesses the moon illuminated by verdant vegetation rather than the artificiality of human civilization.'
    - '정 (meditation/stillness): Refers to a meditative state valued in both Buddhist and Daoist traditions, suggesting spiritual cultivation through withdrawal from worldly affairs.'
